{"title_page": "Maurice E. Baringer", "text_new": "'''Maurice E. Baringer''' (December 4, 1921 &ndash; May 25, 2011) was an American educator and politician.\n\nBaringer was born in [[Arkansas City, Kansas]]. He served in the [[United States Army Air Forces]] during [[World War II]] and was stationed in the Pacific. He served as an anti-aircraft artillery officer. Baringer received his bachelor's degree in business from [[University of Kansas]] in 1943. He then served his bachelor's and master's degree in animal husbandry from [[Iowa State University]] in 1947\u20131949. Baringer worked in the commercial feed business in management, nutrition, and sales. Baringer taught animal husbandry at Iowa State University. He lived in [[Oelwein, Iowa]]. Baringer served in the [[Iowa House of Representatives]] from 1961 to 1969. He served as speaker of the house from 1967 to 1969 and was a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]. From 1969 to 1982, Baringer served as [[Treasurer of Iowa]]. He raised horses and cattle at his farm in [[Woodburn, Iowa]] after his retirement. Baringer died suddenly at [[Mercy Medical Center - Des Moines|Mercy Hospital]] in [[Des Moines, Iowa]].<ref>[https://www.legis.iowa.gov/legislators/legislator/legislatorAllYears?personID=611 The Iowa Legislature-Legislators-Maurice E. Baringer]</ref><ref>[https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/desmoinesregister/obituary.aspx?page=lifestory&pid=151324740 Maurice Baringer-obituary]</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Find a Grave|70460273}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baringer, Maurice E.}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Arkansas City, Kansas]]\n[[Category:People from Clarke County, Iowa]]\n[[Category:People from Oelwein, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Farmers from Iowa]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Kansas]]\n[[Category:United States Army Air Forces soldiers]]\n[[Category:University of Kansas alumni]]\n[[Category:Iowa State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Iowa State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Iowa Republicans]]\n[[Category:Members of the Iowa House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:State treasurers of Iowa]]\n\n{{Iowa-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "'''Maurice E. Baringer''' (December 4, 1921 &ndash; May 25, 2011) was an American educator and politician.\n\nBaringer was born in [[Arkansas City, Kansas]]. He served in the [[United States Army Air Forces]] during [[World War II]] and was stationed in the Pacific. He served as an anti-aircraft artillery officer. Baringer received his bachelor's degree in business from [[University of Kansas]] in 1943. He then served his bachelor's and master's degree in animal husbandry from [[Iowa State University]] in 1947-1949. Baringer worked in the commercial feed business in management, nutrition, and sales. Baringer taught animal husbandry at Iowa State University. He lived in [[Oelwein, Iowa]]. Baringer served in the [[Iowa House of Representatives]] from 1961 to 1969. He served as speaker of the house from 1967 to 1969 and was a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]. From 1969 to 1982, Baringer served as [[Treasurer of Iowa]]. He raised horses and cattle at his farm in [[Woodburn, Iowa]] after his retirement. Baringer died suddenly at [[Mercy Medical Center - Des Moines|Mercy Hospital]] in [[Des Moines, Iowa]].<ref>[https://www.legis.iowa.gov/legislators/legislator/legislatorAllYears?personID=611 The Iowa Legislature-Legislators-Maurice E. Baringer]</ref><ref>[https://www.legacy.com/obituaries/desmoinesregister/obituary.aspx?page=lifestory&pid=151324740 Maurice Baringer-obituary]</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Find a Grave|70460273}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Baringer, Maurice E.}}\n[[Category:1921 births]]\n[[Category:2011 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Arkansas City, Kansas]]\n[[Category:People from Clarke County, Iowa]]\n[[Category:People from Oelwein, Iowa]]\n[[Category:Farmers from Iowa]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Kansas]]\n[[Category:United States Army Air Forces soldiers]]\n[[Category:University of Kansas alumni]]\n[[Category:Iowa State University alumni]]\n[[Category:Iowa State University faculty]]\n[[Category:Iowa Republicans]]\n[[Category:Members of the Iowa House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:State treasurers of Iowa]]\n\n{{Iowa-politician-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1947-1949 \u2192 1947\u20131949", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maurice_E._Baringer"}
{"title_page": "R. Michael Young", "text_new": "{{other people|Michael Young}}\n{{Infobox State Senator \n| name=R. Michael Young\n| image name=\n| state_senate=Indiana\n| state=Indiana\n| district=35th\n| term_start=November 8, 2000<ref>http://www.capitolandwashington.com/offices/all-offices/235/</ref>\n| term_end=\n| preceded=[[Morris Mills]]\n| succeeded=\n| state_house1=Indiana\n| state1=Indiana\n| district1=92nd\n| term_start1=November 4, 1992<ref>http://www.capitolandwashington.com/offices/all-offices/192/</ref>\n| term_end1=November 8, 2000\n| preceded1=''Constituency established''\n| succeeded1=[[Phillip Hinkle|Phillip D. Hinkle]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indystar.newspapers.com/newspage/107484259/?terms=State+Representative+District+92+Young+Hinkle|title=The Indianapolis Star from Indianapolis, Indiana on November 8, 2000 \u00b7 Page 14|author=|date=|website=newspapers.com}}</ref>\n| state_house2=Indiana\n| state2=Indiana\n| district2=48th\n| term_start2=November 5, 1986<ref>http://www.capitolandwashington.com/offices/all-offices/148/</ref> \n| term_end2=November 4, 1992\n| preceded2=Paul Burkley\n| succeeded2=Dean R. Mock\n| party=[[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n| birth_date={{birth date and age|1951|5|14}}\n| birth_place=Indianapolis, Indiana\n| children=3<ref>http://legdb.iga.in.gov/#!/legislator/6533/R.-Young</ref>\n| death_date=\n| death_place=\n| alma_mater=[[Indiana University South Bend]] (BA)<br>[[Indiana University Robert H. McKinney School of Law|Indiana University School of Law]] (JD)\n| occupation=Attorney\n| spouse=\n| residence=[[Indianapolis, Indiana]]\n| religion=\n}}\n\n'''R. Michael Young''' is a [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] member of the [[Indiana Senate]], representing the 35th District since his appointment in December 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/4728/r-michael-young#.UsN-amRDveU|title=The Voter's Self Defense System|author=|date=|website=Vote Smart}}</ref> He succeeded [[Morris Mills]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/107483306/?terms=R+Michael+Young+Morris+Mills+State+Senate+35th|title=The Indianapolis Star from Indianapolis, Indiana on November 5, 2000 \u00b7 Page 210|author=|date=|website=newspapers.com}}</ref> He was elected to the [[Indiana House of Representatives]] in 1986.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/312865395/?terms=Brian+Bosma+House+of+Representatives+Michael+Young|title=The Indianapolis News from Indianapolis, Indiana on November 5, 1986 \u00b7 6|author=|date=|website=newspapers.com}}</ref> In 1992, Young was redistricted and was reelected to the 92nd district.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indystar.newspapers.com/newspage/106952379/?terms=R.+Michael+Young+Dean+R.+Mock|title=The Indianapolis Star from Indianapolis, Indiana on November 4, 1992 \u00b7 Page 16|author=|date=|website=newspapers.com}}</ref> Young previously served on the [[Marion County, Indiana|Marion County]] Board of Zoning Appeals from 1980\u20131982. He ran for the [[United States House of Representatives]] for [[Indiana's 4th Congressional District]] in [[United States House of Representatives elections in Indiana, 2002|2002]]<ref>https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=232266</ref> and in [[United States House of Representatives elections in Indiana, 2010|2010]].<ref>https://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=621033</ref>\n\nOne of 20 Indiana State Senators who according to the Indianapolis Star Newspaper unfairly targeted the specialty license plates of the Indiana Youth Group, resulting in not only the Indiana Youth Group having their specialty plates revoked but also those of 4-H and The Greenway Foundation.  Senator Young was one of 20 Indiana State Senators who signed a letter to the BMV to have the specialty plates for IYG revoked as a direct attack because IYG provides a safe place for LGBT teenagers.\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n* [https://ballotpedia.org/R._Michael_Young_(Indiana) R. Michael Young at Ballotpedia]\n*[https://www.ourcampaigns.com/CandidateDetail.html?CandidateID=40418 Our Campaigns \u2013 Senator R. Michael Young (IN)] profile\n* [http://www.in.gov/legislative/senate_republicans/homepages/s35/ State Senator R. Michael Young] ''official Indiana State Legislature site''\n* {{CongLinks | congbio= | votesmart=4728 | fec= | congress= }}<!--\nLinks formerly displayed via the CongLinks template:\n* [http://www.followthemoney.org/database/uniquecandidate.phtml?uc=139183 Financial information (state office)] at the National Institute for Money in State Politics\n* -->\n\n{{Indiana State Senators}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Young, R. Michael}}\n[[Category:Indiana state senators]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Indianapolis]]\n[[Category:1951 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n\n\n{{Indiana-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{other people|Michael Young}}\n{{Infobox State Senator \n| name=R. Michael Young\n| image name=\n| state_senate=Indiana\n| state=Indiana\n| district=35th\n| term_start=November 8, 2000<ref>http://www.capitolandwashington.com/offices/all-offices/235/</ref>\n| term_end=\n| preceded=[[Morris Mills]]\n| succeeded=\n| state_house1=Indiana\n| state1=Indiana\n| district1=92nd\n| term_start1=November 4, 1992<ref>http://www.capitolandwashington.com/offices/all-offices/192/</ref>\n| term_end1=November 8, 2000\n| preceded1=''Constituency established''\n| succeeded1=[[Phillip Hinkle|Phillip D. Hinkle]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://indystar.newspapers.com/newspage/107484259/?terms=State+Representative+District+92+Young+Hinkle|title=The Indianapolis Star from Indianapolis, Indiana on November 8, 2000 \u00b7 Page 14|author=|date=|website=newspapers.com}}</ref>\n| state_house2=Indiana\n| state2=Indiana\n| district2=48th\n| term_start2=November 5, 1986<ref>http://www.capitolandwashington.com/offices/all-offices/148/</ref> \n| term_end2=November 4, 1992\n| preceded2