{"title_page": "Arthur H. Taylor", "text_new": "{{Other people|Arthur Taylor}}\n<!-- This article was automatically created by [[User:polbot]] from http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=T000065. The prose may be stilted, and there may be grammatical and Wikification errors. Please improve in any way you see fit. -->'''Arthur Herbert Taylor''' (February 29, 1852 &ndash; February 20, 1922) was a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Indiana]].\n\nBorn at [[Caledonia Springs, Ontario]], Canada, Taylor moved with his parents to [[Yates County, New York]], in 1856.  He attended the local school.  He taught school for several years, and then moved to [[Indianapolis, Indiana]] in 1869 to study law.  He was [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admitted to the bar]] in 1873 and commenced practice in [[Indianapolis, Indiana]].  He moved to [[Petersburg, Indiana]], in 1874 and continued the practice of law.  He served as [[prosecuting attorney]] for the eleventh judicial circuit of Indiana 1880\u20131884.\n\nTaylor was elected as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] to the [[53rd United States Congress|Fifty-third Congress]] (March 4, 1893 &ndash; March 3, 1895).  He was an unsuccessful candidate for reelection in 1894 to the [[54th United States Congress|Fifty-fourth Congress]].  He resumed the practice of law in [[Petersburg, Indiana]], until his death February 20, 1922.  He was interred in [[Walnut Hills Cemetery (Petersburg, Indiana)|Walnut Hills Cemetery]].\n\n== References ==\n{{CongBio|T000065}}\n\n{{Bioguide}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{S-par|us-hs}}\n{{US House succession box\n|state = Indiana\n|district = 1\n|before = [[William F. Parrett]]\n|after = [[James A. Hemenway]]\n|years = March 4, 1893 \u2013 March 3, 1895\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{IndianaUSRepresentatives}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Taylor, Arthur Herbert}}\n[[Category:1852 births]]\n[[Category:1922 deaths]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States House of Representatives from Indiana]]\n[[Category:Indiana Democrats]]\n[[Category:Canadian emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:American prosecutors]]\n[[Category:People from the United Counties of Prescott and Russell]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party members of the United States House of Representatives]]\n[[Category:People from Petersburg, Indiana]]\n\n\n{{Indiana-politician-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|Arthur Taylor}}\n<!-- This article was automatically created by [[User:polbot]] from http://bioguide.congress.gov/scripts/biodisplay.pl?index=T000065. The prose may be stilted, and there may be grammatical and Wikification errors. Please improve in any way you see fit. -->'''Arthur Herbert Taylor''' (February 29, 1852 &ndash; February 20, 1922) was a [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] from [[Indiana]].\n\nBorn at [[Caledonia Springs, Ontario]], Canada, Taylor moved with his parents to [[Yates County, New York]], in 1856.  He attended the local school.  He taught school for several years, and then moved to [[Indianapolis, Indiana]] in 1869 to study law.  He was [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admitted to the bar]] in 1873 and commenced practice in [[Indianapolis, Indiana]].  He moved to [[Petersburg, Indiana]], in 1874 and continued the practice of law.  He served as [[prosecuting attorney]] for the eleventh judicial circuit of Indiana 1880-1884.\n\nTaylor was elected as a [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]] to the [[53rd United States Congress|Fifty-third Congress]] (March 4, 1893 &ndash; March 3, 1895).  He was an unsuccessful candidate for reelection in 1894 to the [[54th United States Congress|Fifty-fourth Congress]].  He resumed the practice of law in [[Petersburg, Indiana]], until his death February 20, 1922.  He was interred in [[Walnut Hills Cemetery (Petersburg, Indiana)|Walnut Hills Cemetery]].\n\n== References ==\n{{CongBio|T000065}}\n\n{{Bioguide}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{S-par|us-hs